The paper presents data structures for range-clustering queries, which involve partitioning a set of points in $\mathbb{R}^d$ into subsets based on a cost function. This falls under the umbrella of computational geometry, which suggests cs.CG as a likely category. The paper also discusses approximation algorithms and capacitated clustering, which are topics in algorithms and data structures (cs.DS) and discrete mathematics (cs.DM). Additionally, the paper mentions $k$-center clustering in $L_p$-metric, which is a topic in machine learning and artificial intelligence (cs.LG and cs.AI).
